tweet: As we celebrate African American history & culture today and tomorrow, it is as important as ever to unite as Utahns & Americans to protect the constitutional rights of all people and do all we can to ensure that all are treated as equals, regardless of the color of their skin.

name: Utah Office of State Treasurer
tweet: During the 2016 legislative session, Utah became the 45th state in the nation to have an official state observance of Juneteenth Freedom Day, which is commemorated annually on the third Saturday in June.

name: Utah Office of State Treasurer
tweet: Juneteenth continued to be widely observed in Texas decades later and has since grown within communities throughout the country.

name: Utah Office of State Treasurer
tweet: The Juneteenth announcement was met with jubilation that spread throughout the country as African Americans relocated to neighboring states and became reacquainted with family. The first Juneteenth celebration was a time for reassurance, prayer, and the gathering of family.

name: Utah Office of State Treasurer
tweet: Exactly 155 years ago today, Union soldiers landed at Galveston, Texas with news the war had ended and the enslaved were free, finally putting the Emancipation Proclamation into full effect more than two years after it was issued.

name: Utah Office of State Treasurer
tweet: Today is a day of celebration, remembrance, and reflection. Juneteenth is the oldest-known celebration commemorating the abolition of slavery in the United States and the emancipation of African American slaves throughout the nation.  https://t.co/2UoLFjq9CX
